      <hedline>
        <hl1>An International Court</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rev Peter Laarman letter deplores US resistance to International Criminal Court, subject of Bruce Broomhall's June 13 Op-Ed article</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It was disconcerting to learn from ''Salute to a Rights Campaigner Who Gave Genocide Its Name'' (news article, June 13) that the Bush administration has quietly sought to have our government's signature removed from the treaty establishing the International Criminal Court, and also that the Pentagon wants a ''guarantee that no American will ever be tried'' before it can accept the work of the court.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It was disconcerting to learn from ''Salute to a Rights Campaigner Who Gave Genocide Its Name'' (news article, June 13) that the Bush administration has quietly sought to have our government's signature removed from the treaty establishing the International Criminal Court, and also that the Pentagon wants a ''guarantee that no American will ever be tried'' before it can accept the work of the court.</p>
        <p>As ''Criminal Justice on a Global Scale,'' by Bruce Broomhall (Op-Ed, June 13), makes clear, American qualms about the court's potential reach are irrational, not to say profoundly xenophobic.</p>
        <p>Small wonder that the administration's go-it-alone philosophy is straining relations with our allies: on key questions of human rights, just as on global warming and missile defense, our government acts not just as a bully, which would be bad enough, but also as an ignorant bully, which is inexcusable.</p>
        <p>(Rev.) PETER LAARMAN  New York, June 13, 2001</p>
        <p>The writer is senior minister, Judson Memorial Church.</p>
      </block>
